nce in medicine // Metabolism: Clinical and Experimental. 2017. Vol. 69S, Pp. S36-S40. DOI:10.1016/j.metabol.2017.01.011. 13. Гудфеллоу Я., Бенджио И. Глубокое обучение. М.: ДМК Пресс, 2018. 14. Jiang L., Wu Z., Xu X., Zhan Y., Jin X., Wang L., Qiu Y. Opportunities and challenges of artificial intelligence in the medical field: current application, emerging problems, and problem-solving strategies // Health Information Science and Systems. 2021. Vol. 9, №1. DOI:10.1007/s13755-021-00150-2. 15. Fiske A., Henningsen P., Buyx A. Your Robot Therapist Will See You Now: Ethical Implications of Embodied Artificial Intelligence in Psychiatry, Psychology, and Psychotherapy // Journal of Medical Internet Research. 2019. Vol. 21, №5. DOI:10.2196/13216. 16. Schmidt College of Medicine, Florida Atlantic University. The impact of artificial intelligence in medicine on the future role of the physician // PeerJ. 2021. DOI:10.7717/peerj.11023. Шаблон заполнения был сформирован на основе ГОСТ Р 7.0.5-2008 и актуальных элементов ссылок. Некоторые элементы, как даты обращения к электронным ресурсам, были добавлены для ориентирования читателя, учитывая их важность в контексте изменяемости интернет-источников."},{"prompt":"For the following question: “ Task 1: Ransomware is a computer malware, which prevents or limits users from accessing their system by encrypting victim’s files with a strong encryption key making them inaccessible unless a ransom is paid. This malicious software often installs covertly on a victim’s computer, runs a cryptology attack that adversely affects it, and then requires payment from the victim to get a decryption key. Today, there are dozens of ransomware strains. Globally, ransomware continues to be a problem with new families emerging regularly. There are two types of ransomware in circulation. The common type today is crypto ransomware, which aims to encrypt files. The other is locker ransomware, which is designed to lock the computer, preventing victims from using it. In this assessment, we will only consider the crypto ransomware type. Your task is to design a new crypto ransomware based on the Feistel structure, which utilises a product cipher algorithm that combines three of the classical transposition and substitution ciphers. In this task, you will answer several questions that readers might ask about this ransomware: 1. Distribution scheme: Propose a way to distribute your ransomware to potential victims. Explain both the download and execution procedures. (10%) 2. Obfuscation: Propose a way to keep your ransomware hidden during both the infection and operation phases to prevent removal and analysis. Name some tools that allow you to implement your selected way. (10%) 3. Command and Control (C&C) Communications: Describe communications between the infected machine and the C&C server, e.g., key generation, storage, etc. (10%) 4. Specify what files will your ransomware encrypt. Describe your method to search for local and network drives, get files from a drive, and what are the supported file extensions? (5%) 5. Analysing Ransomware Security: Perform security analysis on your proposed ransomware against common attacks, e.g., brute force, meet-in-the-middle attack, frequency analysis, etc. Is there a way to decrypt the files or identify, detect and remove your ransomware without paying the attacker? (30%) 6. Explain what are the payment instructions like? (5%) 7. Research and identify 2 technical controls and 2 compliance-related practices that can be deployed to reduce the success of ransomware attacks in an organisation. (10%) 8. Implement your product cipher in your preferred programming language. (code and/or screenshots should be provided as an appendix) (20%) Your report should include the algorithm design disclosure; this should cover (not limited to): the operation of the three transformations used by the algorithm, their running order and interconnections, input to each transformation, key generation and length, and the number of rounds. It is essential to develop a schematic diagram that shows the details of your algorithm. Useful resources A list of conventional cryptographic algorithms, https://www.cryptool.org/en/cto/ Cracking codes with Python, https://inventwithpython.com/cracking/ ” Whilst taking the above question specifications into consideration, WHILST LEAVING MY INPUT COMPLETELY UNCHANGED IN ITS CONTENT, ADD EXACTLY AN ADDITIONAL 75 WORDS TO THE “Preventative Actions Against Reverse Engineering:” section WHEREVER NECESSARY AND HIGHLIGHT/ MAKE BOLD ANY ADDITIONS THAT ARE ADDED. Please ensure that during the creation of this entry the following applies: that the tone one would use when answering an important examination question is used and abides by the following: employs a vast range of references (embedded and harvard referenced) utilises impressive grammar/ demonstrates an astonishing linguistic prowess, shows extensive research that is abundant in detail and illustrates amazing attention to detail, is both concise and insightful, demonstrates excellent reflection, showcases linguistic elegance of a publishable quality, and finally has embedded harvard references and a separate references section. Please also to ensure to abide by the following grading criteria to ensure whatever is produced is workings of which are deserving of the highest/ best grading band possible: “A very comprehensive technically correct submission. All major aspects of the assignment covered. Clear expression of ideas. A very high standard of presentation. All problems identified and solutions are feasible and within the restrictions of the assignment. All sources acknowledged and referenced to a high standard.” (please also display the word count minus references.): “Analysing Ransomware Security: The advancing convolution of cryptographic ransomware, notably those founded on Feistel cipher architectures, demands thorough security scrutiny to mitigate prevalent cryptographic incursions (Anderson, 2008; Stinson, 2005). This prototype integrates the principles of transportation and substitution amid a Feistel construct, establishing a labyrinthine encryption approach- this resultantly presents considerable obstacles for adversaries seeking to decrypt files, and/ or locate and eradicate the ransomware sans financial indemnity (Bertino & Sandhu, 2005; Ferguson, et al., 2010). Mitigating Meet-in-the-Middle (MitM) Attacks: This cryptographic model employs successive encryption cycles, interweaving transposition and substitution procedures- such recursive profundity in encryption elevates the computational sophistication requisite for decrypting the cipher devoid of comprehension of the key, accordingly, subverting the efficacy of MitM attacks (Diffie & Hellman, 1976). Therefore, the introduction of non-linear constituents into encryption cycles considerably elevates the integrity of the encrypted data, markedly fortifying resistance to differential cryptanalysis by intensifying the complications in forging plaintext and ciphertext pair relational pairings (Biham & Shamir, 1991). Sequentially, the complexity of each cycle’s output heightens, diminishing the chance of discerning intermediate plaintext states imperative in foiling MitM attacks. Bypassing the Pitfalls of Frequency Analysis: Frequency analysis, an acclaimed instrument in cryptanalysis [the study of decrypting cryptographic systems (Stinson, 2005)] in the face of basic substitution ciphers, encounters a pronounced decline in effectiveness against the multifaceted encryption system of this ransomware in question. The employment of elaborate substitution algorithms, whose variations are iteratively administered throughout encryption sequences, substantially confounds frequency analysis activities. Concurrently, the sporadic variation of key schedules efficiently neutralises the dangers presented by conventional frequency-dependent cryptanalysis practices (Matsui, 1993). Characteristically, the Feistel structure systematically transmutes character frequency distributions across its encryption cycles, masterfully obsoleting frequency analysis for cipher deconstruction (Sinkov & Feil, 2009). Moreover, the presence of polyalphabetic components unremittingly modulates the substitution protocol, consequently corroding frequency analysis initiatives (Singh, 1999). Countermeasures for Brute Force Attacks: Feistel-centric architectures, with their dependency on extensive keys of variable length, inherently possess vigorous defensive measures to combat brute force attacks (Stinson, 2005). The calculated execution of key expansion strategies, by which short keys are methodologically elongated to more intricate, lengthier variants, calls for an exponentially greater computational exertion for brute force deciphering, accordingly, ingeniously enlisting time an ally against any unsanctioned decryption efforts (Hellman, 1980). This defence is fortified by an immense key space, via synthesising multiple conventional ciphers, rendering the notion of a meticulous key search ineffective within any feasible timeframe, consequently affording preservation against brute force attacks. Moreover, the implementation of a versatile key generation model, distinctively allocating keys for individual scenarios, adds a layer of convolutedness- subsequently thwarting brute force attack attempts (Schneier, 1996; Katz & Lindell, 2014). Counteractive Measures for Decryption and Detection: Decryption endeavours, absent the direct procurement of the corresponding decryption key is profoundly taxing due to the aforementioned cryptographic hindrances. Refined obfuscation manoeuvres, conjoined with the core complexities of encryption, not only obfuscate the decryption endeavours, but also mask the ransomware from signature-oriented detection algorithms, thereby fostering a stratified and multi-layered defence schema (You & Yim, 2010). Nevertheless, one cannot afford to ignore conceivable theoretical susceptibilities regarding cryptanalysis; the domain of cryptographic attacks is in perpetual flux, demanding sustained observances and optimisations to the encryption framework applied by the ransomware. In the realm of identifying ransomware, elaborate obfuscation alongside C&C communicative strategies elucidated herein serve to impede conventional heuristic and signature-based technologies (Ucci, et al., 2019). Nevertheless, the utilisation of sophisticated behavioural analysis instrumentation, monitoring system operations for deviations indicative of ransomware, yield a tangible method for discernment and deterrence without acceding to monetary demands. The engagement of decentralised machine learning-oriented models demonstrates the potential to distinguish the nuanced behavioural modalities of ransomware operations, promoting an anticipatory security stance (Apruzzese, et al., 2018). Preventative Actions Against Reverse Engineering: Warding off reverse engineering pursuits- imperative for the exposure and comprehension of the inner machinations of the ransomware- as formerly noted calls for the strategic usage of obfuscation techniques. Harnessing the prowess of refined software protection tools [take Enigma Protector and Code Virtualizer as exemplars], they metamorphose plain code into a confounding conundrum, in doing so vastly inhibiting the reverse engineering process. This strategy adeptly shrouds logical patterns in secrecy whilst drastically augmenting the difficulty quotient and minimising the success threshold for cyber defence bodies endeavouring to crack and/ or invalidate the ransomware without complying to ransom payment (Megira, et al., 2018; Zander, et al., 2007).”.","completion":"Analysing Ransomware Security: The advancing convolution of cryptographic ransomware, notably those founded on Feistel cipher architectures, demands thorough security scrutiny to mitigate prevalent cryptographic incursions (Anderson, 2008; Stinson, 2005). 